---
import Base from '../../layouts/Base.astro';
---

<Base
  title="Services"
  description="Discovery, advisory, and build support for teams designing practical AI automation systems around real operations."
>
  <div class="container-wide">
    <section class="section-band">
      <div class="panel workbench-hero-copy services-hero-full">
        <p class="eyebrow">AI automation services</p>
        <h1>Design and build automation systems around the work people actually do.</h1>
        <p class="lede">
          For teams moving from vague AI interest to mapped workflows, credible implementation choices, and useful first builds.
          The operating model is simple: discover the work, advise on the system, then build the first working use case.
        </p>
        <div class="hero-links" style="justify-content: flex-start;">
          <a href="/contact/" class="hero-btn">Discuss a workflow</a>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="section-band">
      <h2>Who This Is For</h2>
      <p class="section-intro">
        This is for teams that need practical automation judgment, not a generic AI transformation deck.
        The same process works for a founder-led company, an SMB operations team, or an enterprise group preparing a serious internal automation initiative across finance, HR, IT, operations, sales, or marketing.
      </p>
      <div class="proof-strip">
        <div class="proof-item">
          <span class="pill blue">Operators</span>
          <strong>Teams with messy handoffs</strong>
          <p>Manual reporting, queue work, repeated research, intake triage, approvals, or process knowledge stuck in people's heads.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="proof-item">
          <span class="pill sage">Leaders</span>
          <strong>Teams evaluating AI seriously</strong>
          <p>Groups that need a defensible opportunity map, constraints, governance posture, and implementation path.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="proof-item">
          <span class="pill plum">Builders</span>
          <strong>Teams ready to operationalize</strong>
          <p>People who have a process worth improving and need help turning it into a working system.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="section-band">
      <h2>Primary Offering</h2>
      <div class="process-roadmap">
        <article class="panel process-step agent" data-step="01">
          <div class="eyebrow">Discovery</div>
          <h3>Map the operation</h3>
          <p>Run process workshops, identify bottlenecks, capture handoffs, surface exceptions, and score automation opportunities by value, risk, and readiness.</p>
        </article>
        <article class="panel process-step guardrail" data-step="02">
          <div class="eyebrow">Advisory</div>
          <h3>Design the system</h3>
          <p>Translate the map into architecture, tool choices, governance, human review points, success measures, and a buildable implementation scope.</p>
        </article>
        <article class="panel process-step review" data-step="03">
          <div class="eyebrow">Build</div>
          <h3>Ship the first use case</h3>
          <p>Build or guide the first useful automation system: intake, routing, agent instructions, data flow, review artifacts, and operating documentation.</p>
        </article>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="section-band">
      <h2>Engagement Types</h2>
      <div class="feature-grid">
        <article class="feature-card">
          <span class="pill blue">Workshop</span>
          <h3>Automation discovery workshop</h3>
          <p>Best when the team knows AI could help but needs a clear map of where. Output is prioritized use cases, constraints, and next actions.</p>
        </article>
        <article class="feature-card">
          <span class="pill copper">Hackathon</span>
          <h3>Applied automation hackathon</h3>
          <p>Best when a team needs momentum: structured ideation, viable experiments, and promising concepts turned into practical build candidates.</p>
        </article>
        <article class="feature-card">
          <span class="pill sage">Advisory</span>
          <h3>Implementation advisory</h3>
          <p>Best when leadership or delivery teams need help with architecture, vendor/tool choices, governance, rollout sequencing, or build scope.</p>
        </article>
        <article class="feature-card">
          <span class="pill plum">Build</span>
          <h3>Hands-on build support</h3>
          <p>Best when the plan needs to become something real: internal tools, agent workflows, automation scripts, reporting systems, or review systems.</p>
        </article>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="section-band">
      <div class="callout">
        <p class="eyebrow">Automation background</p>
        <h2>Seven years inside the automation wave at Automation Anywhere.</h2>
        <p>
          Years of process workshops, discovery sessions, and automation conversations at Automation Anywhere shaped this operating model.
          That work showed the durable part of automation: how teams identify use cases, align business and technical stakeholders, govern what scales, and avoid brittle demos that never become operations.
        </p>
        <p>
          The broader background spans consulting, solutions engineering, business analysis, project management, and technical delivery across functions and industries including banking, airlines, and telecommunications, with work experience touching the United States, Germany, and Brazil.
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="section-band">
      <h2>Typical Outputs</h2>
      <div class="utility-grid">
        <div class="utility-item">
          <strong>Workflow map</strong>
          <p>Current-state process, bottlenecks, ownership, systems, inputs, outputs, exceptions, and review points.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="utility-item">
          <strong>Opportunity backlog</strong>
          <p>Ranked automation candidates with value, readiness, risk, and recommended next step.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="utility-item">
          <strong>Implementation blueprint</strong>
          <p>Tooling, architecture, data flow, handoffs, governance, rollout sequence, and first-build scope.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="utility-item">
          <strong>Working prototype</strong>
          <p>A first useful system that proves the workflow, review model, and operational value.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="utility-item">
          <strong>Operating docs</strong>
          <p>Instructions, standing orders, review rules, and handoff notes so the system can keep improving.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="utility-item">
          <strong>Executive-ready summary</strong>
          <p>Plain-English findings and recommendations a larger stakeholder group can understand quickly.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="section-band">
      <h2>Start the Conversation</h2>
      <p class="section-intro">
        Send the workflow, team, or operational problem you are trying to improve. The right next step may be a discovery workshop, advisory session, or buildable first system.
      </p>
      <p><a href="/contact/">Contact Jonathan &rarr;</a></p>
    </section>
  </div>
</Base>
